requirement_title: HAB126 C 5320 HAB Staff & Organizational Development / Professional Development Strategic Planning
requirement_description:
The HIV/AIDS Bureau (HAB) is soliciting consulting, coaching, strategic planning and staff engagement services, including leadership development, for the design, development, implementation and continued support of programs and services, as well as other organizational development related activities essential to supporting new and current HAB employees.
HAB cannot carry out its mission without the hard work and dedication of its most valuable resource; its employees.  The Bureau plans to utilize employee and organizational development to improve the engagement, effectiveness, creativity, and capabilities of its staff. Employee development is a key tool for enhancing job-related performance and organizational effectiveness that promotes personal and professional growth; it equips professionals with competencies that allow them to cope with on-the-job situations and manage interpersonal relations. To meet this objective, HAB would like to expand its current organizational and employee development services by supplementing services with additional support.

HAB has two  organizational development staff, and the needs for strategic planning and staff development cannot be fully met by a two person team even with the support of HLI, etc. HAB has a need for a sustained effort as short term efforts have not been able to be sustained due to limited staffing. EHE resulted in approximately 30 new staff and a new organizational structure within OPS and DPD, so HAB needs this preparation work to be successful. 
In addition to the ideas mentioned, this contract will support the implementation of the following tasks - an interactive training platform; course development; internal support for HAB retreats; coaching; and a leadership development program.

requirement_description:
The contractor will ensure effectiveness and efficiency in grantee implementation of program components of the AETC Program by ensuring uniformity and credibility in implementation of proposed strategies. The overall goal of contract is to support the Regional AETCs and local partners efforts to achieve the four programmatic goals:

Goal 1: Expand the number and diversity of health care team members providing HIV care and prevention services
Goal 2: Expand the ability of health care team members to provide effective HIV care and prevention services   
Goal 3: Improve health equity by integrating HIV care and prevention in primary care and other healthcare settings that provide services to underserved populations
Goal 4: Enhance the capacity of the AETC Program to train health care team members to serve people at risk for or with HIV

Proposed services include: 

-National Training
-Technical Assistance (education, training)
-Capacity Building
-Communications /Promotion
-Evaluation and Quality Improvement

MCHB59 C 5778 Health Equity Assessment Leveraging MIECHV Performance Measures 2.0 (HEAL-PM 2.0)
requirement_description:
This contract will provide expert consultation and recommendations to HRSA to support the continued redesign of the Maternal, Infant, and Early Childhood Home Visiting (MIECHV) Program performance measures.  The contractor will conduct external engagements with families participating in home visiting and home visitors and other staff to facilitate feedback on recommendations provided under the previous contract.  Findings from the HEAL-PM 1.0 environmental scan and interested party engagement activities identified community engagement as fundamental to ensuring that the MIECHV/Tribal MIECHV performance measurement systems incorporate a health equity perspective.  This contract will ensure those perspectives are included in HRSA's decision making process.

Final deliverables will include: proposed MIECHV performance measures that reflect cultural diversity and feedback from community engagement; technical assistance tools to support awardees in collecting and using revised measures; resources to support HRSA in analyzing and disseminating collected performance data to advance health equity.

requirement_title: OPAE111 C 5840 Data Visualization Tool to Strengthen Need-Based HRSA Investments
requirement_description:
Congress established the Evidence Act to improve access to data, expand evaluation capacity, and emphasize strong agency coordination for the strategic use of data within the federal government. As HRSA's lead for implementing the Evidence Act, OPAE is requesting $400,000 to fund an analytic tool that will provide actional intelligence in support of HRSA program operations and program oversight, impact, and accountability.

In FY2023, OPAE and OIT partnered to build a proof-of-concept data analytic tool - the Health Equity Mapping Tool - and released it to the public via the HRSA Data Warehouse. The Mapping Tool has generated significant interest across the agency including, for example, from MCHB and FORHP. Building on the proof-of-concept model, the requested FY2024 funding will support development of a Version 2.0 with at least three potential applications: 

	for use by grant applicants to demonstrate their need for HRSA funding in an equitable and objective way using the same standard data sets and tools on health disparities and the social determinants of health; 
	for use by Bureaus and Offices to direct funding to geographical areas with the highest need and to achieve specific performance goals; and
	for evaluators to assess the degree to which HRSA investments have resulted in measurable, impactful public health outcomes.

During FY2024, OPAE will gather input from the Bureaus and Offices on necessary features and data sets to mature the proof of concept into a tool that best meets the unique, practical needs of HRSA programs. 

This request aligns with HRSA's interim strategic plan Goal 4 to Optimize HRSA Operations and Strengthen Program Engagement: Objective 4.1 Improve efficiency and effectiveness of operations; Objective 4.3 Enhance program oversight and integrity, and strengthen program delivery, by building and using evidence; and Objective 4.4 Provide efficient, effective, and responsive customer service to recipients of HRSA funding and other stakeholders.

requirement_title: MCHB59 C 5971 Strengthen System Integration of MIECHV-Funded Evidence-Based Home Visiting Programs with Medical Homes
requirement_description:
There has been recent interest in better understanding the opportunities and challenges with more fully integrated systems that include home visiting programs and medical homes, specifically through co-location in federally qualified health centers (FQHCs). Integrated systems have the potential for better coordination of services, decreased service duplication, reinforcing messages to families, and synergistic impact to maternal and child health outcomes and reduction of health disparities. 
Meaningful partnership can also ensure families most in need of services are identified and enrolled in appropriate programming.  

FQHCs provide comprehensive primary care services to underserved communities and populations. Leveraging medical homes within FQHCs with home visiting programs may optimize collaboration and communication and maximize the potential to achieve positive maternal and child health outcomes among families and young children who live in communities that face greater risks and barriers. However, there is limited information and understanding of what linkages currently exist between FQHCs and home visiting programs, which models of integration have been effective, and best practices. 

Over a 36 month period of performance, this project would leverage existing research on home visiting system integration and service coordination with medical homes to develop and conduct a descriptive study of home visiting programs that have been implemented with medical homes at FQHCs or other primary care settings. The project team would be responsible for reviewing existing literature, engaging key interested parties and consulting with experts, developing a study design and required data collection tools, conducting the study, and producing a final report with findings and recommendations

That service shall be comprehensive and shall include the activities that follow with an appropriate referral enter into RCIS referral system by appropriate providers at Catawba Service Unit: Patient will be fitted for a pair of Diabetic Shoe or Diabetic Inserts once a year. requirement_description: The Indian Health Service (IHS), Tucson Area Office, invites qualified vendors to submit RFQ's for providing a duplicate Dell PowerProtect Data Manager, Data Domain 6400 appliance. This hardware will be shipped and installed in the IHS Albuquerque Data Center for the purpose of providing replication of IHS Tucson Area Office data assets.  Physical installation of hardware in the Albuquerque Data Center will be performed by IHS personnel.  Data storage capacity, Virtual Machines and power will be provided by the Albuquerque Data Center.   Software configuration for data replication is part of this RFI and will need to be performed by the vendor and/or Dell.

requirement_description: The 2024 Nursing Leadership Summit held September 23-26, 2024 within the continental United States. Alternate dates in September 2024 will be considered. The host facility must be located within walking distance to local amenities, restaurants, and public transportation. Walking distance is defined as 0.14 miles or less. The host facility must be in an area that is that is safe for pedestrian activity and with a low crime rate (low crime rate is defined as within the national average for violent and property crime). Four working days will be dedicated to achieving the goals and objectives established by DNS and NNLC. The first date will be utilized by the Division of Nursing Services and the National Nurse Leadership Council for planning, this date will have 30 participants. The remaining three date will have approximately 240 participants in attendance. The attendees will be arriving the day before events and depart day after events.

requirement_title: Portland Area Data - Phone Services with Lumen
requirement_description: The Indian Health Service (IHS), Portland Area Office intends to issue multiple orders in support to extend the Portland Area Wide Telephone Services for up to 3 years with its local exchange carrier per FAR 13.106-1(b), solicitation from single source. Lumen is the Local Exchange Carrier (LEC) for phone services at the Portland Area of Responsibility. The Portland Area Indian Health Service (IHS) is transitioning to the EIS Telecommunication contract for telecommunication services. Each facility will be responsible for managing its voice accounts. There are 8 facilities in Portland Area located in Washington and Oregon. This request does not include equipment, software, or changes to existing services. This request does not require cabling changes or other physical changes. The existing facility phone system will not change. The IHS Office of Information Technology (OIT) is preparing a contracting vehicle process for all IHS facilities. This request is temporary process until the IHS OIT completes their new system. Lumen is the source of existing telephone service for the Portland Area Office.

The goal of this project is to perform mechanical upgrades (repair and replace) to the hospital HVAC system. The 1980 system components are compactly assembled within Penthouses and connected by custom ductwork rather than modern air handlers that are factory built, shipped in modules and assembled on site. Most mechanical systems requiring repair and replacement were originally placed in the 1980 construction. Preliminary analysis and design of certain systems and/or elements may be required. Mechanical systems include heating ventilating and air conditioning (HVAC), steam generators and humidification and the Building Automation System (BAS).

requirement_title: NCIRD SAP Software Licensing and Subscription: Addition of SAP MaxSecure Services to 75D30122F15049
requirement_description:
RMS#1164 - The government plans to pursue a noncompetitive bilateral modification to add this requirement to existing contract 75D30122F15049 awarded to Advantaged Solutions.  The Contractor shall provide support through SAP MaxSecure (NS2).  A modification to exercise and fund the final option period was executed 03/01/2024 for the core requirement of SAP licenses and subscription, annual maintenance, and back-end support.  This bilateral modification will add SAP MaxSecure Services, to reduce risk and improve efficiency and effectiveness in planning the migration of VTrckS from SAP ERP to SAP S/4HANA before and during the VTrckS system integration project.  The order must be issued on a sole-source basis in the interest of economy and efficiency because it is a logical follow-on to
an order already issued under contract 75D30122F15049.

requirement_description:
RMS#1222 - NCIRD IDIQ Task Order: Policy staff work cohesively with the Divisions to promote the Center's priorities through the analysis of policies and programs; strategic communication with external stakeholders; coordination of meetings and briefings; management of clearances, document development and review; formulation of annual budget justifications; and responding to time sensitive political issues or special assignments.  The work requested through this contract will directly support two of the strategic priorities for the office, specifically:
-	Strengthen and expand strategic partnerships across the Center in collaboration with other OD offices and Divisions
-	Help NCIRD achieve goals through strategic engagement with HHS, the Office of Management and Budget (OMB), and Congressional stakeholders

2025 - $141,350.00
2026 - $145,750.00
2027 - $120,120.00

requirement_title: Programmatic and Scientific Staffing Services for the Influenza Division
requirement_description: The ID Epidemiology and Prevention Branch (EPB) aim is to (1) Conduct surveillance, research, modeling and forecasting activities to better understand and monitor the epidemiology of influenza viruses and disease; (2) improve understanding of the effectiveness of influenza antiviral, vaccines, and non-pharmaceutical interventions ; (3) assist state and local health departments to conduct surveillance and with activities related to the detection and response to emerging and novel influenza viruses; (4) support influenza vaccine policy development with ACIP and other groups; and (5) support influenza pandemic preparedness activities, regional teams and cross-cutting program and technical support teams.

requirement_description: The purpose of this project is to monitor the transmission of influenza viruses in household settings. This includes the transmission and viral dynamics of influenza, and how these dynamics are impacted by characteristics of individuals, including vaccination, previous immunity, age, clinical symptoms or lack thereof, and characteristics of infecting influenza viruses.  We seek partners who can collaboratively and efficiently conduct household transmission studies of influenza during periods of virus circulation.  These studies include prospective recruitment and follow-up, collection of respiratory virus specimens, and collection of information about individuals.

requirement_title: Animal & Exposure Facility Support for Morgantown Research
requirement_description: The purpose of this is to provide care and maintenance of animals and laboratory technical support for the research at the laboratories of NIOSH, an institute of the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC). Quality laboratory animals for use in our experiments, and quality technical personnel to aid in experiments, will help provide NIOSH with some of the needed data to recommend appropriate exposure limits in the workplace. The research animals must be maintained under carefully controlled conditions to allow the accurate interpretation of laboratory results. Consequently, it is essential that the animal housing and exposure facilities be properly maintained to avoid any situation or condition that might adversely affect experimental results

requirement_title: Rapid Message/Materials Testing with Public Consumers and/or HCPs
requirement_description: Funding to cover ~8 separate quick turn-around message/materials-testing projects that can be fully completed within ~6-8 weeks involving individual interviews with targeted samples of the general public and healthcare professionals on a variety of different kinds of CDER communications. This testing follows the President's Executive Order of September 15, 2015, to "improve how information is presented to consumers" by considering how content, format, timing, and medium affects comprehension and action by individuals; federal plain language guidelines; and the Plain Writing Act of 2010. The topics of this testing include a variety of safety information about medical use of OTC and prescription drugs, including controlled and addictive substances including the FDA priority areas of opioids, benzodiazepines, gabapentinoids, psychedelics, and stimulants; in line with the SUPPORT Act; and key priorities by the White House, HHS, CDER and FDA, and other federal agencies to advance the goal of ending the opioid and overdose epidemics; and addressing misinformation/disinformation related to COVID and public health emergencies more broadly, which are priority areas for CDER and FDA. This effort also supports FDA initiatives to advance communications related to postmarket drug safety and understanding the needs of underserved and special populations such as those with low education, racial/ethnic minorities, and other vulnerable groups, whose inclusion will be a priority. These message testing projects are conducted by OCOMM for offices and divisions across CDER and at the FDA level, e.g. related to Covid. If not funded, CDER and FDA will have no evidence to determine how well our communications are meeting their objectives related to comprehensibility; impact; attracting and keeping attention; ensuring relevant, needed, desired and culturally appropriate messages; and identifying the most appropriate ways to communicate sensitive or controversial information.

requirement_description: Maintain and expand as needed, a Donation Database Coordinating Center (DDCC) in the United States to monitor HIV, HBV, HCV and other TTIs identified as important to blood safety. The DDCC will function to: a) Monitor and characterize infections (HIV, HBV, HCV, and other selected TTIs) identified at participating blood collection organizations and assess prevalence and incidence rates, overall and by demographic and geographic subgroups. b) Evaluate temporal, demographic, and geographic trends in incidence and prevalence rates for these TTIs over the period of the project. c) Evaluate and monitor risk factor characteristics of donors whose donations are confirmed positive for HIV, recently acquired HBV or HCV, or other markers determined to be of interest. d) Integrate risk factor data and disease marker surveillance information across different blood collection organizations e) Collect and compile bio-specimens and donation datasets from TTI-positive donors in repositories to enable additional researchers to compile donation datasets f) Serve as a resource to the scientific community by enabling collaborations and investigations into additional research questions. As part of the Commissioner's priority to address health misinformation, CDERLearn becomes a critical tool for OCOMM to provide an educational platform that offers a variety of learning opportunities for healthcare professionals, patients/consumers, and academia/students, directly from the source: FDA, to reduce misinformation and build public trust. The goal of CDERLearn is to curate a body of educational modules about human drug regulation, scientific and regulatory activities, and to share FDA expertise in specific subject areas to further instruct the public about the many ways CDER protects and promotes public health. The associated cost supports hosting educational materials for the public, providing essential continuing education (CE) credits for healthcare professionals, and paying for marketing/advertising activities that will enable us to effectively reach the intended external stakeholders. CDERLearn supports HHS strategic goals, FDA's Regulatory Strategic Plan, and OCOMM's Strategic Communications Plan for transparency, increasing public awareness, and strengthening public trust by providing educational courses produced directly by CDER internal experts. It currently hosts programs developed by subject matter experts from the Office of the Center Director (e.g., Drug Shortages), Office of Compliance (e.g., Compounding), Office of Surveillance & Epidemiology (e.g., MedWatch), Office of Medical Policy (e.g., OPDP), Office of New Drugs (e.g., Biosimilars), and Office of Generic Drugs (e.g., Safety Evaluation and Surveillance of Generic Drugs, or Understanding Generic Narrow Therapeutic Index Drugs), etc. Due to these extensive collaborations, CDERLearn serves as a conduit that strengthens cross-center relationships and leverages existing and new partnerships to address mission-critical scientific and regulatory issues.

Executive Order 14036 directs the Secretary of Health and Human Services to act to combat excessive pricing of prescription drugs and enhance domestic pharmaceutical supply chains, to reduce the prices paid by the Federal Government for such drugs, and to address the recurrent problem of price gouging. The executive order also supports lowering the prices of prescription drugs, promoting generic competition and clarifying the approval framework for generic drugs to increase transparency and build patient confidence in generic drugs. CDER's Office of Communications and Office of Generic Drugs proposes to refresh the outdated Generic Drug education campaign in order to meet the intent of the EO and promote patient confidence by educating audiences about the generic drug approval process and the robust safety, efficacy and quality criteria generic drugs must meet to be FDA-approved. FDA-approved generic drugs are copies of brand-name drugs and are the same in dosage form, safety, strength, route of administration, quality, performance characteristics and intended use. The generic drug industry has grown from modest beginnings into a major force in health care. Generic drugs now account for 90% of prescriptions dispensed in the U.S. and saved the nation's health system  trillion from 2005 to 2014. However, research shows misperceptions about generic drugs among consumers who believe generics to be less effective than brand name drugs . Many prescribers report that they sometimes or often prescribe a brand-name drug to a patient when a generic is available because the patient wanted it. The refreshed campaign and website content will help ensure patients can make informed choices about generics. This effort around the safety, efficacy and quality of generic drugs will also help increase prescribers' comfort in selecting safe and effective treatment options. This campaign will help us realize our goals of patient confidence in FDA-approved generic drugs.

The mission of the Center for Biologics Evaluation and Research (CBER) is to protect and advance public health by ensuring the safety and efficacy of biological products, such as vaccines and blood products. CBER's Office of Vaccines Research and Review (OVRR), Division of Viral Products (DVP), is seeking a Researcher Level II to assist the investigators at the Laboratory of Respiratory Viral Diseases at DVP/CBER to perform collaborative mission-critical researches on seasonal and pandemic influenza vaccines in support of World Health Organization (WHO) bi-annual vaccine strain selection. The work requires laboratory and investigative procedures using techniques such as serological assays, BSL-3 environment practice, animal models, immunology and molecular virology, virus amplification and titration, antibody purification and identification. This position is essential to the daily operations of the laboratory. Immediate support is required for continuity of operations within the laboratory.

requirement_description: The New Drugs Regulatory Program (NDRP) Modernization ("the Modernization") is a multi-year, multi-phase regulatory improvement initiative comprised of changes to the structural organization of CDER, process and documentation improvements for key CDER functional activities (i.e. Investigational new drugs, marketing applications, advisory committee meetings, and OND divisional scientific strategies) and enhancements to the administrative and regulatory operations of the Office of New Drugs. The objectives of this effort are to fortify CDER's scientific leadership (through, for example, more integrated, inter-disciplinary work, and more rigorous risk-benefit analysis), to improve operational efficiency, and to invest in vital enablers such as knowledge management and talent development. The Modernization is now managed by a small program management staff, the Special Programs Staff within the immediate office of OND. The Special Program Staff (SPS) is responsible for launching the design and implementation of new initiatives that would otherwise not be implemented, such as those that fall outside the scope of legislated mandates or Agency directives. SPS drives the tactical implementation of initiatives leveraging the support of the Office of New Drugs as the central subject matter experts and beneficiaries of the initiatives, and works closely with OND Policy, Program and Regulatory Operations functions (e.g., business process operations staff, learning and talent development). Upon reaching a steady or stable state of newly implemented initiatives the SPS facilitates a methodical transition to full-scale roll-out working closely with identified long-term business owners. And, lastly, SPS supports continuous improvement by providing support for planning to long-term owners in the collection of ongoing feedback about programs/initiatives and more formal summative evaluations. This purpose of this project is to expand investigations addressing the specific initiatives of FDA Commissioner Califf to identify strategies for providing accurate information to the public during public health emergencies to help overcome false, inaccurate, or misleading information and to increase trust in the agency. According to Commissioner Califf, "The disharmony of noise and unverified or misleading assertions, the torrent of misinformation, and, too often, disinformation that we see today is often intended or designed specifically to undermine and erode trust in science, scientists, and expert agencies such as the FDA," and he has said this problem "poses one of the most serious threats to public health today." Similarly, the U.S. Surgeon General has warned that misinformation is an "urgent threat" to public health that can have "dangerous consequences" for people's health and lives. As a result, the objective of the project will be to build upon findings obtained from studies OCOMM social scientists are currently conducting with consumers and health care professionals to deepen understanding of the effects of health misinformation during public health emergencies related to human drugs and other FDA-regulated products. This FY25 project will include investigation of the ways misinformation spreads and evolves; ways and reasons it impacts people; roles uncertainty and understanding of the scientific process play; comprehension of FDA Emergency Use Authorization vs. drug approval; and sources trusted to provide factual information. Understanding the experiences and needs of underserved and special populations, including those in rural areas, and identifying ways to address them will be a priority. requirement_title: DBPAP / Duration of Pertussis Immunity in Baboons Study
requirement_description: The laboratory of Respiratory and Special Pathogens is engaged in studies with the goal of characterizing differences in duration of immunity of pertussis vaccines and identifying factors contributing to differences in duration. MD Anderson was contracted to enroll a total of 48 baboons in a long-term Duration of Immunity Study. This includes 12 unvaccinated baboons, 12 whole-cell vaccinated baboons, 12 acellular vaccinated baboons and 12 infected and recovered baboons returned to MD Anderson from CBER. To initiate the study infant baboons are enrolled into the study as they are born and they receive their first vaccination at 2 months of age. They are then vaccinated two more times over the next four months. Following the third vaccination, MD Anderson waits six months and then collects samples. The collection of the six-month post-vaccination samples marks the end of the initial phase of the study which is covered by the base contract. The enrollment of baboons was delayed because there was an unusually low number of births in the baboon colony for several months. Both baboon colonies in the U.S. are very small compared to macaque breeding colonies so it's not possible to manage shortfalls by transferring animals from other breeding centers. Unlike macaques, importation of baboons is severely restricted by international treaty so you can't import baboons to manage supply. The only thing that MD Anderson could do was wait and enroll animals as they were born. The animals required for this study have now been born so the schedule moving forward is known. The study timeline is provided. It is evident from the study timeline that there were no baboons enrolled between October and February. That was due to the lack of births. One can also see the last animals enrolled were born this month. They will receive their first vaccination (at 2 months of age) in April. They will receive their last vaccination in September and will reach the six-month time point in March 2023.

As CDER, we recognize the significance of this law in our mission to serve all stakeholders effectively. The 508 Remediation contract focuses on remediating PDF files-essential documents like annual reports, drug reviews, and Advisory Committee presentations. By making these files accessible, we reinforce CDER's commitment to excellence and equity. Section 508 is a legal obligation as well as a reflection of our core values-promote and protect public health by making our communications accessible to all.

requirement_title: Healthcare Fraud Prevention Partnership (HFPP) Trusted Third Party (TTP)
requirement_description: The Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services (CMS), Center for Program Integrity has a need to acquire analytic support and a technical solution for the Trusted Third Party (TTP) program. To satisfy this need, CMS launched the Healthcare Fraud Prevention Partnership (HFPP) with the Department of Health and Human Services (HHS) Office of the Inspector General (OIG), Department of Justice (DOJ), Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI), private health insurance companies, state and local agencies, and other healthcare and anti-fraud groups and associations. The Contractor shall support all aspects of the HFPP, following all requirements set forth by Congress through the Consolidated Appropriations Act, 2021 (CAA). The partnership requires the services of a Trusted Third Party (TTP) to support the HFPP with the analytic and management ability to exchange healthcare fraud, waste, and abuse data and identify innovative measures to detect and prevent healthcare fraud, waste, and abuse.

requirement_description: ESRD Help Desk Re-compete: The Automated Plan Payment System (APPS) is the system that CMS uses to calculate, validate and process prospective monthly payments in advance to Medicare Advantage Plans, Prescription Drug Sponsors, and various demonstrations and other plan types. CMS is required by law to make monthly payments to Plans and Sponsors. The Contractor is responsible for assisting in the correction of ESRD data when a plan reports an incorrect payment. The APPS is the focal point core system for processing monthly plan payments and is key to ensuring that these multi-billion dollar payments can be made accurately and on time.
